# Rider Flutter Standards

## File and widget size

- Keep each Dart file under approximately 300 lines of code.
- Keep each widget, class, and function body comfortably under 300 lines.
- When a screen grows too large, split it into:
  - Smaller widgets for map sections, bottom sheets, and app bars.
  - Shared widgets in `apps/rider/lib/widgets/` for reusable elements.

## Theming and typography

- Do not hard-code colors or fonts in Rider code.
- Always obtain colors from `colorsProvider` (`HeyCabyColorTokens`) and text styles from `typographyProvider` (`HeyCabyTypography`).
- If a new color is needed, add a semantic token in `heycaby_ui` theme data instead of using hex literals.

## Localization

- All user-visible text must come from `AppLocalizations`.
- Do not add inline string literals for UI copy in Rider screens.
- When adding new strings, update all supported languages in the l10n files.

## Navigation

- Use the shared `GoRouter` configuration in `appRouter` for navigation.
- Pass data via typed models and `state.extra` where appropriate instead of raw maps.

## Separation of concerns

- Keep side effects (network calls, identity access, secure storage) in providers, services, or notifiers, not directly inside large build methods.
- Prefer small, focused widgets that compose into screens rather than one monolithic widget per screen.

